Gate `lim->features` assignment in md_init_stacking_limits() on the
queue_limits.features field (introduced in kernel 6.11). On older kernels the
field doesn't exist at all, so the assignment can't be papered over by a header
shim — it has to be excluded at source level. The equivalent flags
(WRITE_CACHE | FUA | IO_STAT | NOWAIT) are applied via blk_queue_*-style calls
inside the queue_limits_set compat shim (dkms/compat/compat.h), so 6.8 still gets
correct cache-flush semantics.

This patch carries ONLY the md.c hunk, which is identical on every tree (the
generic md core is untouched by the meshstor feature branches). The per-personality
`lim.features |=` assignments in raid1.c / raid10.c are gated by 0009 (composed
meshstor-main tree) and 0010 (verbatim upstream `master`) instead: those two files'
queue-limits code differs by composition — meshstor-main refactored
raid10_set_queue_limits to take a `conf` arg, and bare upstream carries a second
`lim.features |= BLK_FEAT_PCI_P2PDMA` (commit b8764f3) between the ATOMIC_WRITES
assignment and the stack call — so a single fuzz-0 hunk can't anchor on both. The
0009/0010 split is selected by `.when` guards on the presence of the meshstor
member-AND helper raid1_can_advertise_p2pdma().

HAVE_QUEUE_LIMITS_FEATURES is set by dkms/Makefile.in's feature_flags target
when the running kernel's <linux/blkdev.h> defines `features` inside
`struct queue_limits`.

--- a/md.c
+++ b/md.c
@@ -6325,8 +6325,10 @@
 void md_init_stacking_limits(struct queue_limits *lim)
 {
 	blk_set_stacking_limits(lim);
+#ifdef HAVE_QUEUE_LIMITS_FEATURES
 	lim->features = BLK_FEAT_WRITE_CACHE | BLK_FEAT_FUA |
 			BLK_FEAT_IO_STAT | BLK_FEAT_NOWAIT;
+#endif
 }
 EXPORT_SYMBOL_GPL(md_init_stacking_limits);
